 Geoderma, 24 (1980) 45--69                                                         45  Elsevier Scientific Publishing Company, Amsterdam -- Printed in The Netherlands    PROPERTIES AND CLASSIFICATION OF SOME DESERT SOILS IN  COARSE-TEXTURED GLACIAL DRIFT IN THE ARCTIC AND ANTARCTIC    J.G. BOCKHEIM  Department of Soil Science, University of Wisconsin, Madison, WI, 53706 (U.S.A.)  (Received May 16, 1979; accepted November 12, 1979)    ABSTRACT    Bockheim, J.G., 1980. Properties and classification of some desert soils in coarse-textured  glacial drift in the Arctic and Antarctic. Geoderma, 24: 45--69.    Polar Desert soils in the Arctic (66and 74 latitude) are contrasted with Cold Desert  soils in the Antarctic (77). The soils are derived from sandy-skeletal glacial drift and have  not been influenced by cryoturbation. Pedogenic horizons are limited to a desert pavement  (designated D) and to a weak B horizon in the oldest soils of both groups. Solum thickness  increases with age in the two soil groups; however, because of a slightly greater amount of  soil moisture, the increase in solum thickness is greater for Polar Desert soils. Soils of both  groups often contain "dry" permafrost. The Polar Desert soils at 74 and most of the  Cold Desert soils are neutral to mildly alkaline and the Polar Desert soils at 66~N are  strongly to medium acid. Although soluble salts increase with age in soils of both groups,  the increase is more marked in the more arid Cold Desert soils. Results from this study  and a survey of the literature show that sodium is the prevalent cation in water extracts  of Cold Desert soils and in Polar Desert soils above ca. 80. Chloride is the major anion  in Cold Desert soils in the McMurdo Sound vicinity and in noncalcareous Polar Desert  soils. Ion ratios indicate that salts in these soils are contributed by marine aerosols. The  soils examined contain less than 5% clay-size (&lt; 2 urn) material. Mica, vermiculite and  kaolinite are the predominant phyllosilicate minerals in the clay fractions of Polar Desert  soils, and mica, vermiculite and montmorillonite are most abundant in Cold Desert soils.  A scheme contrasting clay-mineral alteration in soils of the two groups is provided. In the  Canadian system, the Cold Desert soils are Static Cryosols, and the Polar Desert soils are  either.Static Cryosols or Dystric Brunisols. In the U.S. system, the soils are Pergelic  Cryorthents. Suggestions are given to modify the U.S. system so as to better distinguish  polar soils.    INTRODUCTION    Polar Desert softs in the Arctic and Cold Desert softs in Antarctica formed in  a cold, arid climate, have a sparse vegetation, and have poorly expressed pro-  fries which are often alkaline and saline, low in organic matter, and underlain  by permafrost. Tedrow (1968) pointed out the morphological affinities of  Polar Desert and Cold Desert softs.  The objective of this study is to contrast the morphological, chemical, and  physical properties and the clay mineralogy of Cold Desert and Polar Desert    0016-7061/80/0000--0000/$02.25 1980 Elsevier Scientific Publishing Company    46    soils which are derived from sandy-skeletal glacial drift and which have been  relatively unaffected by congeliturbation. It should be pointed out that areas  of clayey and loamy soils occur in the high Arctic (Tarnocai, 1978) but that  examples of the more abundant coarse-textured soils were selected for this  comparative study.    BACKGROUND    Tedrow (1977) provided a comprehensive review of polar soils. He proposed  three pedologic zones in the Arctic: the tundra zone, the subpolar desert  zone, and the polar desert zone (Fig. 1). The southern boundary of the tundra  17~    60   90   120   90 30           0               30 150           180           150   60   90   120   47    zone is delineated by a latitudinal treeline, The southern limit of the polar  desert zone corresponds to the July isotherm of 4. The polar desert zone  corresponds geographically to the high Arctic and botanically to the rock  desert (Tedrow, 1977). In the Western Hemisphere, the polar desert zone  (ca. 74--83) includes the Queen Elizabeth Islands and northern Greenland.  The subpolar desert zone was recognized by Tedrow (1977) as transitional  to the tundra zone and the polar desert zone and also as corresponding to  the mid-arctic or the stony sedge-moss-lichen tundra. This zone (ca. 65--74)  includes most of Baffin Island, Melville and Boothia peninsulas; and  Somerset, Prince of Wales, Victoria and Banks islands.    Fig.2. Polar Desert soil (profile 73-8), Cornwallis Island, N.W.T., Canada (74).    Fig.1. Zonation of soils in the Arctic and in Antarctica (after Tedrow, 1977 ) and loca-  tion of study areas. T = tundra pedologic zone; SPD = subpolar desert zone; PD = polar  desert zone; CD --- cold desert zone; 1 = southwestern Cumberland Peninsula, Baffin  Island, N.W.T., Canada; 2 = Cornwallis Island, N.W.T. ; 3 = "dry valley" region, south  Victoria Land, Antarctica.    48    The predominant soil of the polar and the subpolar desert zones is the  Polar Desert soil (Tedrow, 1966, 1977). The Polar Desert soil is well-drained,  has a sparse vegetational cover, a desert pavement, and poorly expressed hori-  zons (Fig.2). The soil is commonly neutral to alkaline, saline and low (less  than 1%) in organic matter. In the subpolar desert zone (Fig. 3), the Polar  Desert soil has a greater amount of organic matter, a less strongly developed  desert pavement, lower pH values and more moisture in the subsoil (Tedrow,  1977). Permafrost in Polar Desert soils may be "dry" or ice-cemented.  Soil zonation is not as readily apparent in Antarctica. Tedrow and Ugolini  (1966) described soils of Antarctica as belonging to the cold desert zone.  In addition, Tedrow (1977) proposed the existence of a less arid polar desert  zone between 60 and 65 latitude, which includes the tip of the Antarctic  Peninsula and the South Shetland Islands (Fig. 1). The major upland soil in  icefree areas of the cold desert zone is an Ahumic soil, so named because it  lacks a humus layer (Tedrow and Ugolini, 1966). However, the Ahumic soil  is not necessarily abiotic. The Ahumic soil of the Cold Desert (referred to  here as simply the Cold Desert soil) has a strongly developed desert pavement,  poor horizonation, negligible organic matter, a mildly acid to alkaline reac-  tion, high salinity and "dry" permafrost within the upper 1 m (Fig. 4).  Tedrow (1968) arranged well-drained polar soils in a hypothetical bio-  climatic gradient from the tundra to the subpolar desert to the polar desert  to the cold desert. Along this gradient calcification, alkalization and salini.  zation were depicted as increasing in intensity and the organic matter contri-  bution as decreasing.    Fig.3. Polar Desert soil (profile 74-40), Baffin Island, N.W.T., Canada (665'N).    49    Fig.4. Ahumic Cold Desert soil (profile 77-52), Taylor Valley, south Victoria Land,  Antarctica (773'S).    Although a number of polar pedologists have used the zonal classification  of Tedrow (1977), other soil classification systems have been utilized in the  polar regions, including the U.S. System (Rieger, 1974), the Canadian system  (Tamocai, 1978), the Soviet system (Rozov and Ivanova, 1967), and the zonal  system of Campbell and Claridge (1969). The zonal system of Tedrow (1977)  will be used here, because of its common usage in the polar softs literature  and because, unlike the other systems, it distinguishes soils of the high Arctic  from those of Antarctica.    STUDY AREA    Polar Desert soils were examined in the subpolar desert zone on south-  western Cumberland Peninsula, Baffin Island, N.W.T., Canada (66) and in  the polar desert zone on Cornwallis Island in the Queen Elizabeth Islands,  N.W.T. (74) (Fig.l). Cold Desert softs were examined in the "dry valleys"  of the Trans-Antarctic Mountains in south Victoria Land, Antarctica (77).  Climatic data