nd, Polar Desert soils range in age from about  1,000 to 100,000 yr BP (Bockheim, 1979a). Cold Desert soils examined in  Antarctica range from 3,100 to about 300,000 yr BP (Bockheim, 1977, 1979b).    METHODS    Soils were described in detail using criteria established by the U.S. Soil  Survey Staff (1951, 1975) and modified for polar soils (Bockheim, 1979b).  Sampling was conducted during the period August 1973--December 1977.  More than 800 samples were collected from over 200 profiles. The data pre-  sented here were selected as representative of Polar Desert and Cold Desert  soils. Although some of the data were published previously, many of them are  given here for the first time.  Particle-size distribution was determined by the modified Bouyoucos  hydrometer method (Day, 1965). Electrical conductivity, pH, and water-  soluble ions (Na Ca2 Mg2 K CI-, SO~-) were measured on 1:5 soil:water  extracts using standard methods for water analysis (American Public Health  Association et al., 1975). Concentrations of sodium and potassium were  measured by flame photometry and those of calcium and magnesium by  atomic-absorption spectroscopy. Sulphate was measured by the turbidometric  method (nephelometry) and chloride by the potentiometric method (chlorido-  meter). With the exception of profiles 73-7 and 73-8, free carbonates were  negligible and are not reported. Free-iron oxides were extracted with a citrate--  dithionite solution buffered with sodium bicarbonate (Mehra and Jackson,  1960). Iron was detected on an atomic-absorption spectrophotometer.  Samples of the clay (&lt; 2 ~m) fraction were treated and mounted on microscope  slides for X-ray diffraction analysis using standard methods summarized by  Whittig (1965).    53    RESULTS AND DISCUSSION    Soil morphology    Polar Desert soils older than 10,000 yr BP and Cold Desert soils older than  100,000 yr BP have a desert pavement and B horizons that fail to meet re-  quirements of a cambic horizon (Table III). Younger soils show no evidence  of horizonation. The desert pavement increases in development with soil age  and degree of exposure to katabatic winds. Not only are clasts in well-developed  desert pavements more closely knit, but they may also show desert varnish,  exfoliation, pitting, and ventifaction. Because there is no uniformly accepted  soil horizon symbol in the literature for expressing the desert pavement, the  symbol D is used here. This symbol was previously used for consolidated  parent rock below the C horizon (U.S. Soil Survey Staff, 1951). Although  it is no longer used with that meaning, the symbol may appear in the older  literature.  Thickness of solum increases with age in both soil groups; the rate of in-  crease is greatest in Polar Desert soils (Fig. 5). The linear regression equation  for the Polar Desert soil is Y = 8.08 + 0.00106 X, where Y = solum thickness  (cm) and X = time (yr 104). The correlation coefficient (r) is 0.97. The  equation for the Cold Desert soil is Y = --1.03 + 0.91 X (r = 0.97). Whereas  softs on Baffin Island which are 5,000--10,000 yr BP in age have sola 25 cm  in thickness, no profile development was observed in 18,000 year old soils of  Antarctica.  The product of the code of hue and chroma, color development equiva-  lences (CDE) are a measure of the magnitude of color development in soils  (Buntley and Westin, 1965). Color development equivalences of Cold Desert  soils and Polar Desert soils on Cornwallis Island are similar (Table III). How-  ever, Polar Desert soils on Baffin Island have a higher CDE than Polar Desert  soils of the high Arctic or Cold Desert soils of an equivalent age.  Soil texture is controlled by lithology of the parent material and weather-  ing. In general, the fine-earth fraction of Polar Desert and Cold Desert soils  examined in this study is dominated by sand (Table III). Coarse fragments  (&gt; 2 mm) commonly comprise from 25 to 75% of pedons in these soils. Cold  Desert soils in Antarctica and Polar Desert soils on Cornwallis Island are struc-  tureless and single-grained. However, due to the presence of very fine (&lt; I mm)  roots and a greater amount of organic matter, Polar Desert soils in the sub-  polar desert zone of Baffin Island have a weak-to-moderate, fine granular  structure.  Salt efflorescences were present on the surfaces of fine-textured soils on  Cornwallis Island after several days of clear, windy weather but were not seen  on southwestern Cumberland Peninsula, Baffin Island. Salt encrustations occur  beneath coarse fragments in Cold Desert soils with ages greater than 18,000 yr  BP (Bockheim, 1979b). Salt flecks 2--5 mm in diameter occur in the matrix  of soils older than 135,000 yr BP. Although soils older than 300,000 yr BP    TABLE III    e.gn    Morphology of Polar Desert and Cold Desert soils derived from coarse-textured glacial drift  Profile  Horizon   Depth  Munsell       Hue X      Soil              Structure                 Roots  (cm)    color         chroma    textural class    Polar Desert soils  74-18   A1          0--10  10YR 5/2      6         silt loam         massive-weak, fine gran.   plentiful v. fine, med.  IIC        10--26  10YR 4.5/2    6         loamy sand      weak, fine granular       plentiful v. fine  73-7    C1          1--21  7.5YR 4/2     8         gravelly loam    mod., fine crumb         few v. fine  C2         21--42  10YR 4/3      9         v.gr. sandy loam rood., v.fine crumb       v.few v.fine  C3ic       42+     10YR 4/2      6         v.gr.sandy loam  massive                   none  73-8    C1          1--23  2.5Y 5/2       4         gravelly sand     single grain               none  C2         23--40  10YR 6/3      9          gravelly sand     single grain                none  C3         40--53  5Y 7/3          3          sand              single grain                none  C4ie       53+     5Y 7/3         3         --                massive                   none  73-9    C1         1~-