m and magnesium are predominant in Polar  Desert soils on Baffin Island. Magnesium and sodium are major constituents  of water extracts of Polar Desert soils on Cornwallis Island. Tedrow (1970)  reported an abundance of calcium followed by sodium in salt crusts from north-  west Greenland, 78 latitude. Day (1964) reported sodium as the dominant  cation in water extracts in two of three soils on northern Ellesmere Island  (819'N). The prevalence of sodium in Antarctic soils is a further indication  of the extreme aridity of the region. In Antarctica, chloride is the dominant  anion in soils located within about 75 km of the open sea. Chloride also is the  most abundant anion in Polar Desert soils reported here and in those analyzed  by Tedrow (1970) in northwest Greenland. Because CaCO3 was detected only  in two profiles (73-7 and 73-8), it is not reported here. However, calcification  is a dominant process in Polar Desert soils derived from calcareous materials  (Everett, 1968; Tedrow, 1970).  Ionic ratios of water extracts of Polar Desert soils of Baffin Island (Bock-  heim, 1979a) and of Cold Desert softs in southern Victoria Land (Bockheim,  1979b) suggest that the Na Mg2 and C1- have originated from marine aero-  sols. Based on ionic ratios, Ca2and Kare of rock weathering origin; SO~-  is due to marine aerosols and rock weathering. Everett (1968) considered Na and SO~- in soils of Ellef Ringnes Island to have resulted from rock weather-  ing because the island is ice-locked. However, Wilson and House (1965) demon-  strated that snow at the South Pole, which is 1,600 km from the ocean in  summer and twice that distance in winter, contained salts contributed by  marine aerosols. Claridge and Campbell (1977) showed the probable path-  ways followed by salts in Cold Desert soils.  Salt efflorescences of soils on Prince Patrick Island are mainly mirabilite,  Na2SO4 10H20 (Tedrow, 1966). Mirabilite is also the dominant salt in ef-  florescences, flecks, patches, and pans of softs in Taylor Valley (Bockheim,  1977) and in Wright Valley, Antarctica (Bockheim, 1979b). The origin of  the mirabilite in the two regions is not known. However, mirabilite is known  to precipitate first from freezing sea water (Thompson and Nelson, 1956).  It is possible that occluded mirabilite is blown across the sea ice, accumulating  in softs of coastal areas of the Arctic Ocean and the Ross Sea, Antarctica.  Dithionite-extractable iron (Fed) is more abundant in Polar Desert soils  of Baffin Island than in Cold Desert soils of Antarctica of an equivalent age  (cf. profiles 74-40 and 77-46; table IV). In both regions Fed increases with  soft age. The rate of increase is greater in Polar Desert soils, due to a greater  amount of soil moisture. A detailed study of a quartz diorite rock in south  Victoria Land, Antarctica, showed few changes in chemical composition fol-  lowing weathering, except for oxidation of iron in biotite and pyrrhotite  (Kelly and Zumberge, ] 961).    Particle-size distribution    Although all of the soils contain less than 5% clay, Polar Desert soils have  more clay than Cold Desert softs of equivalent age and initial material (cf.,    61    profiles 77-46 and 74-41; Table V). The greater amount of clay in Polar Desert  softs may be due to increased chemical weathering enhanced by the slightly  greater amount of soil moisture. Polar Desert soils also have greater quantities    TABLE V    Particle-size distribution and clay mineralogy of Polar Desert and Cold Desert soils    Profile  Horizon   Depth     Sand            Silt        Clay  (cm)      (2--0.05 mm)    (0.05--    (&lt;0.002 mm)  0.002 ram)    Clay minerals1    Polar Desert soils  74-18  A1        0--10     51           49       0          M,k  IIC       10--26     85           15       0           M,k,v  73-7    C1          1--21      50              49         1             M,K,c  C2        21--42      48             48        4            M,K,c  C3ic       42+         