 soils with a high pH and in the  absence of leaching, conditions which exist in many Cold Desert soils. In Polar  Desert softs of Baffin Island, the ratio of the 001 X-ray diffraction peak  height of kaolinite (7.2 A ) to that of mica (9.9 A ) increased from less than 1  in 1,000 year old soils to 6 in 100,000 year old soils (Bockheim, 1979a).  Bockheim proposed that the kaolinite may have been produced by weathering  of feldspar or of mica, or it may have been crystallized from A1 and Si  solutions or gels at ambient thaw-period soil temperatures. Kaolinite minerals  occur predominantly in soils which are low in Ca and Mg and which have  undergone some leaching. These conditions are more likely to occur in softs  of the subpolar desert zone than in softs of the polar or cold desert zones.  The kaolinite in Polar Desert softs of Cornwallis Island may be inherited from  the sedimentary rocks contained in the drift.  Clay-size mineral alteration in Polar Desert and Cold Desert soils may be  depicted as in Fig. 7.  The degree of clay-mineral alteration in polar soils has been debated for  twenty years. In the polar desert zone, Tedrow et al. (1968) and Everett  (1968) were unable to detect consistent weathering differences in the clay  fraction of Polar Desert softs as a function of soil depth. In contrast to these  findings, Isherwood (1975), Bockheim (1979a), and Evans and Cameron  (1979) reported a reduction in mica and an increase in vermiculite with soil  age in Polar Desert softs on southern Baffin Island. Glazovskaya (1958),    Muscovite  mica  Hydrated mica  Vermiculite  , MontmorilLonite  Chlorltized (Fe) montmoPillonite  COLD DESERT    Feldspar    Kaolinite  POLAR DESERT    Fig.7. Clay-size mineral alteration.    63    Claridge (1965), Ugolini and Jackson (1977), and others presented evidence  favoring transformation of clay minerals in Cold Desert soils. In contrast,  Everett (1971) reported few changes in clay mineralogy of Cold Desert soils  ranging in ag