t of the  Cryosol. Tedrow (1977, p. 115,118) advocated distinguishing patterned  ground formation from soil formation. He viewed cryoturbation as a mechani-  cal influence and not as a soft-forming process. Cryoturbation leads to the  degradation of soil horizons rather than their formation.  In the U.S. soil taxonomic system (U.S. Soil Survey Staff, 1975), most of  the soils analyzed in the present study contain greater than 35% coarse material  and are Pergelic Cryorthents. Profile 77-36 has an ice-core at 8 cm and is  not a soil according to the U.S. system.  There is nearly universal agreement among polar soil scientists that the arid  climate is a predominant soil-forming factor in high latitudes. Tedrow (1966)  recognized the importance of calcification, salinization and alkalization in  Polar Desert soils, as did Claridge (1965) in Cold Desert soils. Claridge and  Campbell (1968) found Cold Desert softs to be somewhat comparable to  those occurring in temperate deserts.  Some Polar Desert and Cold Desert soils could be recognized as special  arid members of the Entisols and others as weakly developed members of  the Aridisols. Polar Desert and Cold Desert softs without B horizons could be  recognized at the subgroup level as an extragrade, i.e., Aridic Pergelic Cryor-  thent. This would differentiate Polar Desert soils from Alpine soils (also Pergelic  Cryorthents), such as those occurring in the Rocky Mountains, U.S.A., with  udic soil moisture regimes. Polar Desert and Cold Desert softs with B horizons  could be placed in the Aridisols. However, Aridisols must have either an  aridic or a torric soil moisture regime. An aridic soil moisture regime does not  include soils with a pergelic soil temperature regime (U.S. Soil Survey Staff,  1975, p.55). Therefore, the aridic soil moisture regime would have to be  modified to include soils with pergelic soil temperature regimes.  The most logical great group for Polar Desert and Cold Desert soils with  B horizons would be the Camborthids, which are Aridisols with cambic  horizons. Presence of a cambic horizon is precluded from polar soils derived  from coarse-textured parent materials such as those in this study. The defini-  tion of the cambic horizon would have to be changed so as to include: (1) softs  with textures coarser than loamy fine sand, and (2) soils without the develop-  ment of structure but with a dry consistence which is weakly to strongly  coherent, i.e., not noncoherent. In temperate regions, as well as high-latitude  regions, this would distinguish stable sandy soils from those derived from  loose, shifting sands (Psamments). Emphasis on properties of the cambic  horizon wotfld thereby be given to: (1) the residual concentration of ses-  quioxides, silicate clays, or both; (2) the higher chroma or redder hue than  an underlying horizon in the same sequum; (3) the alteration of the original    TABLE VI  Classification of Polar Desert and Cold Desert soils    65    Soil taxa                             Profiles*    Non-soil  Aridic Pergelic Cryorthent;  ice-cemented permafrost  Aridic Pergelic Cryorthent;  dry permafrost  Pergelic Camborthid; dry  permafrost  Salic Pergelic Camborthid;  dry permafrost    77-36 (CD)  74-18 (PD), 73-7 (PD), 73-8 (PD),  73-9 (PD), 77-46 (CD)  76-21 (CD)    74-41 (PD), 74-40 (PD), 74-43 (PD),  75-15 (CD), 77-52 (CD)  77-14 (CD)    *PD = Polar Desert; CD = Cold Desert.    rock structure. This definition follows points 2, 3, and 4 for B horizons,  as given in the U.S. soil taxonomy (U.S. Soil Survey Staff, 1975, p.460). If the  soil temperature regime is cryic or pergelic, the base of the cambic horizon  does not have to be at least 25 cm below the surface (U.S. Soil Survey Staff,  1975, p.33).  Desert softs of the Arctic and Antarctic could be distinguished at the sub-  group level on the basis of salt content. A salic horizon must be at least 15 cm  thick and must contain a secondary enrichment of salts more soluble in cold  wat