imation. Antarctic soils commonly  contain less than 2% field moisture (Ugolini, 1964). Cruikshank (1971) re-  corded field moisture contents ranging between 10 and 18% in Polar Desert  softs on Cornwallis Island.  Although published soft-moisture data are not available for Polar Desert  soils in the subpolar desert zone, the climatic data in Table I suggest that  these softs are more moist than Cold Desert soils of the same parent material.  A greater amount of moisture in Polar Desert soils in the subpolar desert zone  would enable them to become more deeply weathered than Cold Desert soils  of an equivalent age. This is reflected in the greater amount of dithionite-ex-  tractable iron and clay in Polar Desert soils, particularly in the subpolar  desert zone, as compared to Cold Desert soils.  Soluble salts are more abundant in Cold Desert softs than in Polar Desert  soils of an equivalent age. Salt patches and salt-cemented pans have not been  reported in soils of the high Arctic. The rate of accumulation of soluble salts  is about 500 times as great in Cold Desert soils as in Polar Desert soils (Fig.6).  Despite the greater concentration of salts in Cold Desert soils, they appear to  have originated from the same source as those in Polar Desert soils. Sodium  and CI- are the dominant ions in water extracts, and mirabilite (Na2SO4- 10H20)  is the dominant salt of surface encrustations of Cold Desert and of Polar  Desert soils at latitudes above ca. 78. Based on ionic ratios, the salts appear  to have originated from marine aerosols.  Leaching is not readily apparent in Cold Desert softs and in Polar Desert  softs of Cornwallis Island. Salts contributed by marine aerosols may be car-  ried downward in the soil profiles by water released from small amounts of  melting snow and may accumulate over long periods of time. Some of the  moisture may be contributed by melting during the downward recession of the  ice-cemented frost table through time. Ugolini and Anderson (1973) showed  that Naand C1- migrate upward in frozen Cold Desert soils via unfrozen  films of water on clay colloid surfaces. In older soils these processes lead to the  formation of a salic horizon or a salt-cemented pan. Because of a greater amount  of precipitation, lower pH values, and lower concentrations of soluble salts,  leaching is more evident in Polar Desert soils of the subpolar desert zone than  in the other softs considered. However, Polar Desert softs of the subpolar  desert zone are nevertheless aridic in that they are probably dry in all parts of  the solum more than half of the time and are never moist in some or all parts  for as long as 90 consecutive days. The low (5.5--6.0) pH values of several  Cold Desert softs is due to the salt effect rather than to leaching.  Wind is an important soft-forming agent in Antarctica in redistributing    67    snow, in abrading rocks, and in producing a desert pavement. The desert  pavement in Cold Desert softs is more strongly developed than that in Polar  Desert soils of an equivalent age.  Polar Desert and Cold Desert softs contain an abundance of vermiculite  and mica. Whereas Polar Desert soils also have kaolinite, Cold Desert soils  often contain montmorillonite. The presence of montmorillonite in Cold  Desert softs may be due to the greater aridity in Antarctica than in the high  Arctic. Despite the cold temperatures and lack of liquid water, clay-mineral  alterations occur in the two soft groups. Micas may become hydrated and  expanding layer species may be produced. The silt content of the soils analy-  zed in the present study is generally greater in Polar Desert soils than in  Cold Desert softs. The silt probably originates as loess from floodplains of  braided Arctic streams. Broad floodplains providing a source of silt do not  exist in Antarctica.  A soil as arid and salt-enriched as the mature Cold Desert soil does not  seem to exist in the Northern Hemisphere. As Tedrow (1977) pointed out,  the Southern Hemisphere analog of the Polar Desert soil may occur in  Antarctica at latitudes of 60--65. The search for Polar Desert softs in  Antarctica should be made on well-drained landscapes older than 120,000  yr BP, possibly in Enderby Land or along ihe Antarctic Peninsula.  In order to differentiate among polar softs, the following modifications  of the U.S. soft taxonomic system are suggested:  (1) The aridic nature of weakly developed (i.e., without B horizons) Cold  Desert and Polar Desert softs be recognized at the subgroup level by the  extragrade adjective "aridic".  (2) The aridic soil moisture regime be changed so as to include dry and  cold soils, i.e., softs with a pergelic soil temperature regime.  (3) The cambic horizon be redefined so as to include structureless, but  coherent, soils coarser than loamy fine sand.  (4) Polar softs with a salic horizon be recognized as extragrades at the sub-  group level with the adjective "salic".  (5) Softs containing ice-cemented permafrost be distinguished from those  with "dry" permafrost at the family level.  These changes would be minor but would adequately separate the more  arid Cold Desert softs from less arid Cold Desert and Polar Desert soils and  would show the desert nature of the soils. Finally, the changes would reflect  differences in degree of development of the soils.    ACKNOWLEDGEMENTS    Baffin Island research was funded by contract 74-112 to J.T. Andrews, Uni-  versity of Colorado, by Parks Canada, Department of Indian Affairs. Antarctic  research was funded by contract DPP 74-20991 to G.H. Denton, University  of Maine, by the Division of Polar Programs, National Science Foundation.  T.M. Ballard, University of British Columbia, provided chemical data for the  softs on Cornwallis Island. J.E. Leide read the manuscript.    68    REFERENCES    American Public Health Association, American Water Works Association and Water Pol-  lution Control Federation, 1975. Standard Methods for the Examinatio